-ups of novels and YouTube songs to negotiations of authorial control and interpretative authority between media producers and fan communities to perspectives on the fictional and legal framework of brands and franchises. In this fashion, the collection expands the horizons of both adaptation and transmedia studies and provides reassessments of frequently discussed (BBC's Sherlock, the Alien franchise, or LEGO) and previously largely ignored phenomena (self-censorship in transnational franchises or YouTube cover videos).  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Jun 2021) 4aDigital and Social Media. 4aFan and Audience Studies. 4aFilm, Media and Communication. 4aLiterary History and Criticism. 4aMedia Studies. 7aCOMPUTERS / Digital Media / Video & Animation.2bisacsh  aAdaptation Studies.  aFan Studies.  aMedia Convergence.  aMedia Franchising.  aTransmedia.1 aConstandinides, Costas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFehrle, Johannes, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFehrle, Johannes, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGoggin, Joyce, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHeinze, Rüdiger, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPoore, Benjamin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchober, Regina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchäfke-Zell, Werner, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchäfke-Zell, Werner, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSoller, Bettina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aVoigts, Eckart, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe Gruy